      "writtenOn": "2018-08-18T21:12:37Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This is going to be fragile either at the system image side (what if KernelParams.txt format changes in the future?) or at the emulator side (what if the emulator updates its method for parsing kernel parameters?)\n\nIt\u0027s much less coupling / complexity to have the system image build process generate a new kind of file just for verified boot parameters, and for that to be a defined file format that doesn\u0027t depend on other kernel parameters.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 15,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 18,
        "endChar": 35
      },
      "revId": "027f7160abd9644996cc7275912f2666951784ee",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "4d7fadd8_b861ba1f",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 18,
      "author": {
        "id": 1342319
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-08-20T18:19:32Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I want to think on this a little more.  But to answer your questions.\n\n\u003e What if KernelParams.txt format changes in the future?\n\u003e What if the emulator updates its  method for parsing kernel parameters?\n\nWhy would these things happen?  If we need to have a new format, we could use a different filename, correct?\n\nThis makes the kernel params a \"black box\" according to the emulator.  Contract is between the system image and the provided kernel - both provided by the build process.  The emulators plays the role of transporting the data.\n\n\u003e It\u0027s much less coupling / complexity to have the system image build process generate a new kind of file just for verified boot parameters, and for that to be a defined file format that doesn\u0027t depend on other kernel parameters.\n\nI think it might be more coupling and complexity.  Here is why:\n\nIf we make the paramters known to the emulator, it needs to \"understand\" what these parameters are and how they might vary between different kernels.  Example: If a new kernel is released with a new feature (e.g. FEC), then the emulator code will have to be changed to recognize these parameters and old emulators will no be able to support the feature at all.  Basically a 2 way contract (sys image, kernel) becomes a three way contract with the emulator needing to stay in sync.",
      "parentUuid": "ab5804d6_e9b07d3c",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 15,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 18,
        "endChar": 35
      },
      "revId": "027f7160abd9644996cc7275912f2666951784ee",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "cb4fea95_d3708649",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 18,
      "author": {
        "id": 1082465
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-08-20T18:28:08Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I think if you\u0027re introducing a new file read to the emulator, with no explicit format, the burden of proof is on you to make sure it is stable against changes in any component.\n\nOn the last point, protobuf is a good way to manage changes in the features for the kernel.\n\nI guess we already have a 3-way contract between system images, kernel, and the emulator, except if we make it a black box as you\u0027re suggesting, we invite silent breakages once the kernel command line format given from the system image doesn\u0027t match either the kernel command line format or handling in the emulator.\n\nSo perhaps it is not less or more coupling and complexity, it\u0027s making the current coupling/complexity more explicit, and making future maintainers of system images/kernels/emulators spend less time chasing down weird failures.",
      "parentUuid": "4d7fadd8_b861ba1f",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 15,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 18,
        "endChar": 35
      },
      "revId": "027f7160abd9644996cc7275912f2666951784ee",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "92ce1386_58da00fb",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 18,
      "author": {
        "id": 1082465
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-08-20T18:35:20Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Here\u0027s another scenario: Suppose we enable a new kernel command line feature, but it requires some changes to hypervisor on the host. Maybe some kind of paravirtualized clock or something like that.\n\nWith this current method of just copy/pasting all kernel parameters, we will at some point get mysterious bug reports of the emulator not working on certain machines (this is not theoretical, kernel features have broken KVM on some but not all KVM versions before). Then we debug for months trying to hunt it down until we realize it only happened for a particular subset of Linux users on particular kernel versions, in which case we\u0027d realize it was the kernel parameters.\n\nInstead, if the kernel parameters were a protobuf, the emulator wouldn\u0027t even try to consume any new kernel parameters unless the protobuf were updated, so older emulators wouldn\u0027t break due to that. The kernel parameters would generally be reified, allowing us to accept or reject each one for compatibility.\n\nI realize that if there is some critical fix that requires a kernel parmeter, the protobuf will be old in the current emulator and that would break. But we could just update the emulator side directly instead, if the fix is that critical.",
      "parentUuid": "cb4fea95_d3708649",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 15,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 18,
        "endChar": 35
      },
      "revId": "027f7160abd9644996cc7275912f2666951784ee",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "b9d4cba3_1a10f485",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 23,
      "author": {
        "id": 1082465
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-08-18T21:12:37Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This is dangerous; if we simply read the file raw, it might not be formatted properly, or even contain malicious payload.\n\nInstead there should be an explicit format for verified boot information, and an explicit process for writing and reading that info. I recommend protobuf.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 20,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 23,
        "endChar": 68
      },
      "revId": "027f7160abd9644996cc7275912f2666951784ee",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "29f3240e_efdec109",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 23,
      "author": {
        "id": 1342319
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-08-20T18:19:32Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e This is dangerous; if we simply read the file raw, it might not be formatted properly, or even contain malicious payload.\n\nWith the raw system.img and kernel sitting there as peers, is the \"malicious payload\" really a concern?\n\n\u003e Instead there should be an explicit format for verified boot information, and an explicit process for writing and reading that info. I recommend protobuf.\n\nDoes the emulator have good support for protobuff already?",
      "parentUuid": "b9d4cba3_1a10f485",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 20,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 23,
        "endChar": 68
      },
      "revId": "027f7160abd9644996cc7275912f2666951784ee",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "412a402a_02a0ec40",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 23,
      "author": {
        "id": 1082465
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-08-20T18:28:08Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Well, I just mean that in general appending a raw string from a file out of nowhere it is very easy to break something---for example, what if someone else modifies the file but either adds extra carriage returns or newlines that dont\u0027 conform to expectations (like running on Windows?).\n\nOur current file reading avoids this, by having things like \"IniFile\" or protobuf. \n\nYes, the emulator already has good support for protobuf. Go to our repo and find . | grep \"\\.proto\" and there will be several examples. I strongly recommend using a protobuf to introduce these sort of things.",
      "parentUuid": "29f3240e_efdec109",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 20,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 23,
        "endChar": 68
      },
      "revId": "027f7160abd9644996cc7275912f2666951784ee",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
